🏏 GULLYCRIC: Product & Architecture Blueprint1. The Core PhilosophyTraditional cricket apps are built for professional stadiums, 11-player squads, strict ICC rules, and perfect Wi-Fi. GullyCric is built for the streets, the local grounds, flexible rules, and spotty internet. It is an offline-first, hyper-local scoring engine that turns chaotic neighborhood matches into digitally tracked, broadcast-ready events.2. The Tech Stack & ArchitectureTo handle the robust demands of offline syncing and real-time broadcasting, the underlying architecture needs to be rock-solid.Mobile Frontend: Built to be fast and responsive, utilizing cross-platform capabilities to hit both Android and iOS simultaneously.Local Database (The "Offline Engine"): SQLite will run locally on the device. This is the most critical piece of the app. Every run, wicket, and 2D map coordinate is written to SQLite first. If the internet drops, the app doesn't freeze; it keeps saving locally.Backend API & Logic: A Java and Spring Boot architecture will serve as the heavy-lifting engine for user authentication, match logic validation, and data processing.Cloud Database: MySQL will act as the central source of truth in the cloud, handling complex relational data (users, teams, match histories, ball-by-ball logs).Real-time Syncing: WebSockets will maintain an open connection between the mobile app and the Spring Boot backend, listening for the moment the SQLite database detects a network connection to push its local data to the MySQL cloud database.3. Deep Dive: Key App MechanicsA. The "Gully Rules" Match SetupWhen a user taps "Host a Match," they are not forced into rigid structures. They are presented with a highly customizable setup wizard.Dynamic Squads: Teams can be 5v5, 8v8, or uneven like 7v9. The system handles arrays of any size.Guest Players: The host can input "Dummy" or "Guest" names for players who do not have the app. These profiles are generated temporarily for the match instance.Rule Toggles:Over Limit: Custom input (e.g., 6 overs, 10 overs).Wide = Extra Run? (Boolean toggle).Wide = Extra Ball? (Boolean toggle).No Ball = Free Hit? (Boolean toggle).Pitch Type: Rubber ball, tennis ball, hard tennis, or leather.B. The Scoring Interface & The Audit TrailThe scoring screen takes over the entire UI, dropping the bottom navigation bar to maximize focus.One-Tap Actions: Large touch targets for 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, Wide, No-Ball, Bye, Leg Bye, and Wicket.The Edit System (Audit Trail): Arguments happen. If the opposing team contests a boundary, the host can tap a previous ball and edit the outcome. However, to maintain integrity, that specific ball object in the database gets an isEdited: true flag. In the public scorecard, it displays a subtle [Edited] badge, ensuring everyone knows the record was altered post-delivery.C. The 2D Interactive Map (The Visual Play-by-Play)This is the app's flagship feature. Instead of just reading "4 runs," viewers see the data.Pre-Ball Setup: The scorer sees a top-down view of the pitch. They can quickly drag fielder icons to approximate positions (e.g., placing a guy at deep mid-wicket).Post-Ball Gesture: If the batter hits the ball, the scorer swipes their finger from the batting crease to the point on the field where the ball was stopped or crossed the boundary.The Data Payload: This swipe generates a JSON payload capturing the exact $X$ and $Y$ coordinates of the gesture path, which is synced to the database and rendered live on the screens of anyone watching the match remotely.The Toggle: Because this is cognitively heavy for a fast-paced game, a master "Enable 2D Tracking" switch sits at the top of the screen. If the bowler is rushing, the scorer can toggle it off and just log raw runs.D. Hyper-Local DiscoveryThe app acts as a radar for local cricket.Geospatial Queries: Using the device's GPS, the app queries the backend for any matches with an is_live = true and is_public = true status within a 5km to 10km radius.The Map View: A user sitting at home can open the app, look at a map view of their local area, see three matches happening nearby, and tap into any of them to watch the live 2D scorecard.4. UI/UX and Design SystemThe design must command authority while remaining incredibly clean.Color Palette: A pure Dark Mode UI (deep charcoals and blacks) to reduce screen glare under the harsh outdoor sun, accented with high-contrast neon greens or electric blues for active buttons.Typography: This is critical for scannability. All text, from player names to the scorecard numbers, will strictly use highly legible, premium sans-serif fonts like Inter, DM Sans, or Manrope. No decorative fonts; just clean, utilitarian readability.Navigation: * Idle State: A 3-tab bottom bar (Home, My Cricket, Profile).Active Match State: A swipeable top-tab layout (Live, 2D Map, Scorecard, Info).5. Conceptual Database Schema (MySQL)To make this work seamlessly, the relational database needs to be structured efficiently.1. Users Table:user_id (Primary Key)username (Unique, e.g., @virat_local)phone_numberbatting_style, bowling_styledefault_location_lat, default_location_long2. Matches Table:match_id (Primary Key)host_id (Foreign Key -> Users)location_lat, location_longstatus (Scheduled, Live, Completed)rules_json (Stores the custom gully rules)3. Balls Table (The core data engine):ball_id (Primary Key)match_idover_number, ball_numberbatter_id, bowler_idruns_scored, extras_typeis_edited (Boolean)shot_trajectory_json (Stores the X/Y coordinates for the 2D map)6. Go-To-Market StrategyWhen the MVP is ready, do not try to launch it globally on day one.The Alpha Test: Take the app to a local ground right in your immediate vicinity, like around Kandukur. Test the SQLite offline syncing in real-time under a tree where the internet is terrible.The "Host" Acquisition: Focus entirely on the guys who always volunteer to keep score in the notebook. If you win over the scorekeeper, you automatically acquire the other 20 players on the field who want to see their stats.Viral Loops: After a match, generate a sleek, visually appealing "Match Summary" card image (featuring the typography and dark mode aesthetic) that players can instantly share to their WhatsApp statuses or Instagram stories, with a link to download the app.